<DOCNO> AP900331-0016 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a committee created by congress is ending its 
15month study of the federal courts by recommending major 
reductions in the workloads of federal judges 
in a 203page report to be sent monday to president bush 
congress and chief justice william h rehnquist the panel included 
these recommendations 
shift more drug cases from federal to state courts and give 
state court systems the money needed to cope with the increased 
number of prosecutions resulting from the shift 
transfer many of the disputes over social security benefits 
from the courts to administrative procedures and encourage similar 
outofcourt resolution of jobbias claims 
create an office of judicial impact assessment within the 
federal court system to advise congress about proposed laws and to 
point out drafting defects that might breed unnecessary 
litigation 
repeal mandatory minimum sentencing provisions now in effect 
for numerous federal crimes and have the us sentencing 
commission redraft guidelines that would not be binding on federal 
judges 
the committee said more federal judges are needed but not above 
the number of new judgeships already requested it also said that 
the federal court workload is at a much more critical level in 
appellate rather than trial courts 
the report said congress and the president should fill judicial 
vacancies and approve requested additions quickly but it added 
the committee does not regard additional judgeships as a 
longterm solution 
discussing the judicial fallout from the bush administrations 
war on drugs the report said minor drug cases find their way 
into federal court because congress has provided funds for federal 
and not for state prosecutions 
some of the funds that congress has approved for drug 
enforcement should be used to provide assistance for drug 
enforcement at the critical state and local level it added 
the committee opposed creation of a proposed national appeals 
court that would serve as a buffer between the 12 regional federal 
appeals courts and the supreme court 
but the report recommended that congress authorize an unusual 
fiveyear experiment as an alternative it would allow the supreme 
court to resolve conflicting rulings among two federal appeals 
courts by ordering a third appeals court to tackle the same issue 
and render a nationally binding decision 
the third courts ruling would be final unless the supreme court 
granted a rehearing 
the committees report is a response to what committee members 
called mounting public and professional concern with the federal 
courts congestion delay expense and expansion 
the 15member committee was led by joseph f weis jr a federal 
appeals court judge from pittsburgh it included other judges 
lawyers and law professors 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

