history and the passage of more than 40 
years have finally left jeno szebedinzsky late in his life a 
winner 
since the late 1940s szebedinszky has been an exile settling 
into an adopted country while stubbornly carrying a torch for his 
native hungary 
during all those years first in pittsburgh and recently in 
indiana szebedinszky published a small hungarian language 
newspaper that struggled to preserve hungarian culture among his 
fellow emigrants and battle the authoritarian regime that ruled his 
homeland 
i love america i want to be and maybe i am a good 
american he said in the basement where he punches the text of 
his eightpage paper into a video display terminal 
but my home my mother home is hungary that lives in our 
souls 
the sudden collapse of authoritarian regimes across eastern 
europe surprised szebedinszky as much as anyone now with the iron 
curtain corroded by acid anger of citizens demanding political and 
economic reform szebedinszky feels vindicated in his loyalty 
through the early 1950s he dreamed of returning to hungary to 
publish his newspaper the revolt of 1956 brought a few summer days 
of promise before soviet tanks in the streets of budapest crushed 
the uprising his hopes of an early end to exile were dashed 
but his vigor and determination as a publisher were not he 
proudly tells of wearing out three linotype machines publishing in 
pittsburgh being part of an energetic hungarianlanguage press 
that included some 50 newspapers across the country many published 
daily 
we were working against the communists he said 
