<TEXT>
the pentagon says it is dropping its export 
license review process for certain items deemed to have minimal 
security risk that may be headed to the soviet union or eastern 
europe 
the reviews involve certain types of computers medical 
equipment such as cat scanners and equipment for cancer treatments 
and other industrial items such as machine tools and 
telecommunications equipment the defense department said in a 
statement friday 
the pentagon said it was delegating its review authority in 
these areas to the commerce department 
the change in procedure will not remove requirements for export 
licenses for the items but shifts the review process to the 
commerce department said an official familiar with the decision 
that means the commerce department may issue the export licences 
without referring the export application to the defense department 
for review the pentagon has suggested that the change be 
implemented immediately the statement said 
the reviews are required for export items considered 
dualuse meaning they could have both civilian and military 
applications 
the move is based on our experience with items that we have 
approved after going through the review process said the 
official who spoke on the condition of anonymity it eliminates 
bureaucracy 
the pentagon will continue to review licenses for items 
considered to have higher security applications such as 
supercomputers 
it will no longer review the export license requests for such 
computers as the ibm 3031 4331 and 4341 series considered on the 
low end of mainframe computer systems 
however export licenses for such computers as ibms 4381 and 
4370 series will continue to be reviewed by the pentagon because 
they are on the higher end of midrange computers officials said 
the authorization has also been shifted to commerce for review 
of licenses for the temporary export of products that might be 
shown at exhibits and trade shows in eastern europe or the soviet 
union the statement said 
the change is intended to assist our exporting community and 
improve the competitive position of us industry in international 
trade by expediting the licensing process in areas that involve 
minimal security risk the statement said 
</TEXT>
