department 
soybean plantings are expected to drop 2 percent to 594 million 
acres the departments agricultural statistics board said friday 
except for last year 1990 soybean plantings still would be the 
largest since 1986 
total wheat plantings for the 1990 harvest including winter 
wheat planted last fall and springplanted varieties were forecast 
at about 776 million acres up 1 percent from last year 
according to usda records the allwheat acreage would be the 
largest since 792 million acres were planted for the 1989 harvest 
the 1990 winter wheat crop was reported planted on 572 million 
acres up 4 percent from a year ago but durum wheat planted this 
spring was indicated at 335 million acres down 12 percent other 
types of spring wheat were estimated at 17 million acres down 4 
percent from last year 
farmers have been encouraged by relatively strong corn and wheat 
prices as well as an easing of acreage requirements under federal 
commodity programs in the case of soybeans however record world 
oilseed production has reduced prices from last season 
the 1990 planting figures were based on an annual march survey 
of approximately 75000 farmers to help determine how much land may 
be used for crops this year 
