a truck carrying 2900 gallons of diesel fuel over 
siberias frozen lake baikal has sunk through a fissure in the ice 
and may pollute the lake that holds onefifth of the worlds fresh 
water tass reports 
leakage from the tanks which came to rest 150 feet below the 
surface and 350 feet from shore has been limited the official 
soviet news agency said friday 
the tanks are reliably plugged and the small amount of 
fuel that has surfaced is being localized and pumped to the 
shore the agency said 
but larisa urbakhanova head of the irkutsk regional nature 
conservancy district told tass that the consequences of such a 
bomb are very unpredictable in baikal 
the lake 2500 miles east of moscow and north of the mongolian 
border is 390 miles long 50 miles across at its widest and more 
than 4800 feet deep at points scientists estimate it holds 
onefifth of the worlds supply of fresh water 
tass said the fuel truck moving over baikal was part of a convoy 
carrying fuel supplies to a settlement on the lakes edge but did 
not say exactly where it sank 
baikals ice is thick enough in winter to drive on but drivers 
must watch for cracks tass said truck drivers who treated the 
lake as they would a normal highway were to blame for the accident 
tass said 
the two lead trucks in the conovy managed to maneuver their 
vehicles around the cracks but the third plunged through the ice 
the driver escaped it said 
