<TEXT>
harry bridges a crusty labor movement 
legend who organized waterfront unions on the west coast and led 
san francisco into a general strike in 1934 has died at age 88 
bridges died of emphysema at his home friday 
bridges founded the international longshoremens and 
warehousemens union in 1934 and was its president until 1977 
he was one of the great figures of the american labor 
movement said john hennings secretarytreasurer of the 
california labor federation 
he organized the entire pacific coast not just san francisco 
against the opposition of the shipowners said henning he said 
bridges created a lasting institution to carry on not just a 
strike of the moment 
bridges also is credited with helping organize many of the sugar 
and pineapple plantation cannery and mill workers in hawaii 
during the 1950s 
born the son of a prosperous real estate agent on july 28 1901 
in melbourne australia bridges went to sea and in 1920 arrived in 
san francisco two years later he became a longshoreman when 
conditions on the docks were considered the worst in the nation 
on july 5 1934 two dock workers were killed and 100 wounded 
when police charged a picket line the california national guard 
was called out prompting a general strike 11 days later 
the strike ended in three days with an agreement on a contract 
that established a unionoperated rather than employerrun hiring 
hall 
in a 1973 address to longshoremen in san francisco bridges 
said experience has taught that the union worker has one weapon 
no one else has and that is laying down his tools and quitting his 
job 
beginning in 1939 the federal government tried to kick bridges 
out of the country for 16 years charging the union leader was a 
communist and had falsely denied being a party member when he 
applied for citizenship he was once jailed for 20 days as a 
communist conspirator 
bridges acknowledged receiving help from communists in 1934 but 
always denied being a member of the communist party 
the us supreme court twice reversed orders for his deportation 
although bridges and the ilwu had appeared to have mellowed 
since the 1934 general strike the union exhibited renewed 
militancy in the summer and fall of 1971 when a strike shut west 
coast ports for 100 days 
</TEXT>
