<TEXT>
incomes fell again in latin america last year 
deepeningt an overall decline for the decade of the 1980s 
according to a report published saturday by the interamerican 
development bank 
production in the area grew by only 07 percent for the year 
since population grew by about 24 percent a year more than three 
times as fast the average persons income went down 
incomes declined by 8 percent over the 10 years back to the 
level of 1978 
the regions disappointing overall growth masks good 
performance in a number of countries the report said 
it added that many have acted to improve their performance in 
the 1990s but it warned 
without sustained expansion in investment output and 
employment the deterioration in living conditions suffered by 
large segments of the regions population during the 1980s will 
continue in the decade ahead 
the last two countries to emerge from dictatorship chile and 
paraguay turned in the best records 
after a sharp decline in the first half of the 1980s production 
in chile perked up to an exceptional 85 percent last year that 
growth rate combined with a population increase smaller than most 
countries in the area gave it by far the best increase in incomes 
but according to the world bank the average chilean received 
the equivalent of only 1510 in 1988 the latest year for which 
figures are available that is well below the level for the area 
the average brazilian earned 2280 the average mexican 1820 
and the average us citizen 19780 
production in seven out of 25 countries declined last year with 
the biggest drop in peru 14 percent perus record was due in part 
to a continuing leftist rebellion by shining path guerrillas 
brazil and mexico latin americas most populous countries 
managed 3 percent increases in production despite problems with 
debt and inflation 
the bank itself owned by 44 member countries disbursed a 
record 25 billion in loans and spent a record 61 million on 
technical aid last year it has loans outstanding on 122 billion 
worth of projects designed to raise living standards in the area 
after a threeyear slump the amount of new loans approved rose 
in 1989 to 26 billion 
the increases came after three years of negotiation by the 
united states and other contributing governments to get more power 
over the banks lending 
they can now delay a proposed loan for as long as a year the 
bank has also begun a program of quicklydisbursed loans 
conditioned on promises by the borrowing countries to change their 
policies and put themselves in better condition to repay 
