the war on drugs picks up new recruits 
here sunday when each person who buys something in jackson county 
begins chipping in to help authorities arrest jail and treat 
abusers 
the kansas city metropolitan area faced with one of the 
nations worst drug problems is raising taxes by an estimated 14 
million a year to help authorities tackle a drug culture boosted by 
the infiltration of los angeles gangs 
the onequartercent rise in sales tax will generate nearly 100 
million over its sevenyear life from overthecounter sales in 
jackson county which incorporates kansas city and its suburbs 
the nations 29th largest metropolitan area ranks sixth in the 
availability of crack and police believe that onethird or moer of 
last years 141 killings were drugrelated 
i am not aware of any approach like it in the united states 
said larry myers administrator of the jackson county juvenile 
court i guarantee there are other communities watching to see 
what the outcome is 
voters in jackson county authorized the tax in november since 
then officials have been putting together plans to use the money 
it will enable the county prosecutor to add about 25 prosecutors 
to his staff and the kansas city police department and the jackson 
county drug enforcement task force to hire 30 more officers each 
that will cost each department 15 million a year 
the campaign focuses primarily on enforcement but 25 million 
a year is earmarked for drug rehabilitation programs 1 million 
for community crime prevention programs and 15 million for a 
deferral program that would allow firsttime offenders to receive 
drug counseling and avoid criminal charges 
