the soviet union in an effort to stop smuggling 
that has left store shelves bare throughout the country has 
announced that soviet tourists will be forbidden from taking most 
consumer goods abroad 
the list of banned goods seems endless soviet tourists are now 
barred from leaving the country with everything ranging from car 
batteries to tires mushrooms caviar electric wire bicycles 
cooking oil fabrics and nearly all food products 
valery draganov deputy head of the customs authority announced 
the clampdown on exports friday evening and said it was made 
necessary by chronic shortages of consumer supplies throughout the 
soviet union 
these are extraordinary emergency measures needed to 
stabilize the consumer market he said 
he said the restrictions would not apply to purchases made in 
soviet hardcurrency stores which do not accept rubles and 
generally cater to foreigners or to companies authorized to 
conduct international trade 
the move seems designed to appeal to soviet shoppers who often 
spend hours standing in line outside stores with meager supplies 
but for soviets who travel abroad the announcement was 
devastating 
soviets are only permitted to leave the country with the 
equivalent of 30 to 200 dollars depending on the length and type 
of trip 
to save money many soviets bring food with them while others 
take along expensive consumer items to pick up spare cash soviet 
goods are generally cheaper than their western counterparts 
although they are usually of a lower quality 
draganov said the new restrictions will last throughout 1990 
the consumer market is becoming more and more naked he 
said the situation is becoming even more complex since we 
witness an increased activity of mafia groups 
he said underground groups have been known to purchase large 
shipments of consumer goods from factories and ship them out of the 
country before they reach soviet stores 
we had to stop this mass export of commodities immediately 
draganov said 
at chop a border crossing station in the western ukraine 
customs officials recently confiscated 200 sets of linens 20 
bicycles and six gasolinepowered saws from soviet tourists 
dragonov said tourists were trying to bring out virtually 
everything one can think of 
he said they also have been caught at border crossings smuggling 
cheeses buckets mousetraps electric irons toys socks and 
metalwork equipment 
notice that these goods disappear very quickly from the 
shelves of our shops he said 
