<TEXT>
the new local tax system that has angered many 
britons and prompted protests and riots across the country goes 
into effect sunday in england and wales 
scotland has had the tax for a year 
anger over the tax has contributed to a record 28point lead by 
the main opposition labor party over prime minister margaret 
thatchers governing conservatives according to a harris poll last 
weekend 
the community charge is levied by local governments on every 
adult in a household it replaces a single tax paid by each 
household and based on the value of the property 
that means that now a family with four members over age 18 
living in a small apartment will pay four times as much as a single 
person living in a large house 
a duke in a 100room mansion would pay as much as a street 
sweeper in a cottage if they live in the same borough 
the amount each person will pay is the same throughout a 
community but it varies widely from borough to borough depending 
on the budget needs of the area 
critics of the new tax have dubbed it the poll tax after a 
percapita tax that set off a peasants revolt in 1381 
lowincome and disabled people can receive rebates of up to 80 
percent on the new tax but critics say it is unfair because unlike 
the income tax which is used to pay for national government 
expenditures it does not take into account an individuals ability 
to pay 
legislation written by mrs thatchers government created the 
tax with the aim of reducing central government subsidies to local 
government but members of local councils determine how much to 
charge 
the government expected the labor party to suffer in elections 
because highspending councils with a wide range of public services 
are mostly run by labor members who would have to set a high poll 
tax to pay for them 
but many of the highest increases have been set by conservative 
councils to maintain their services 
the public was initially assured by civil servants and 
conservative lawmakers that the increases would be quite small 
scotland has had the tax for a year 
the peasants revolt of 1381 followed the imposition of the last 
poll tax in england when every person over the age of 15 was 
ordered to pay 
crying hang all the lawyers 100000 peasants marched on 
london they pillaged manor houses burnt the court rolls 
containing their names to destroy the evidence for taxation and 
murdered lawyers magistrates and other officials 
archbishop of canterbury simon of sudbury a lawyer was also 
chancellor of england and regarded by the rebels as one of those 
responsible for imposing the tax the rebels dragged him from the 
tower of london and beheaded him on tower hill 
