retired army chief gen chavalit 
yongchaiyudh became deputy prime minister and defense minister 
friday in a controversial move that students and critics called a 
setback for thai democracy 
chavalit took up the new posts under a command issued by the 
countrys constitutional monarch king bhumibol adulyadej said 
state radio thailand monitored in bangkok 
chavalit retired tuesday as army commander in chief he was 
offered the cabinet posts by prime minister chatichai choonhavan 
who hopes chavalit will help shore up a government destablized by 
allegations of corruption inefficiency and labor disputes 
chatichai yielded his defense ministry portfolio to chavalit 
who also is now one of four deputy prime ministers 
radio thailand said the deputy army chief gen suchinda 
kraprayoon is the new army chief while the armed forces chief of 
staff gen sunthorn kongsompong takes on the post of acting 
supreme commander 
thailand has a long tradition of generals dominating politics 
but hopes for a new course were raised after chatichai in august 
1988 became the first prime minister in 12 years to also be an 
elected official 
chavalits moves to join the cabinet prompted the students 
federation of thailand to renew calls for a constitutional 
amendment requiring all ministers to be elected members of the 
parliament 
members of the federation staged a protest outside government 
house thursday holding up banners that called chavalit a 
destroyer of democratic culture and chastized him for jumping 
the queue to political power 
the thai media usually is timid in criticizing the military but 
the nation an independent englishlanguage newspaper stated its 
views in a hardhitting open letter to chavalit published thursday 
it said many people are suspicious of your motives is this 
your short cut to political power 
your going straight into the government will imply that either 
a top army commander can always demand a seat of political power 
almost at will or that an elected civilian government cannot 
survive without the support of the military or both neither of 
these bodes well for the political future of thailand 
chavalit was appointed army chief in 1986 when the thenprime 
minister prem tinsulanonda fired gen arthit kamlangek for 
publicly challenging the government 
