<TEXT>
the violently bad blood between greyhound lines 
inc and striking drivers reveals more than just a sense of worker 
desperation in a troubled moneylosing business 
it suggests the government has what amounts to a dualstandard 
on safety for passengers who can only afford to take the bus 
more than 200 incidents of violence have characterized the 
monthold strike against the nations only intercity bus service 
union and management both have deplored the violence which has 
frightened thousands of riders away and left others wondering 
whether theyll get shot bombed or harassed 
but federal officials havent done much to stop it except seek 
to restart contract talks 
that attitude contrasts sharply with the stand on safety taken 
by the government in other strikes where the public interest is 
affected perhaps the most notable recent example is the yearold 
walkout at eastern airlines 
when that strike started the transportation department warned 
it wouldnt tolerate illegal impediments to mass transit much less 
violence some lawmakers urged federal intervention to delay the 
strike fearing the impact on their constituents its not 
coincidental that most of the riders affected were business people 
commuters and vacationers along the affluent eastern seaboard 
the unions protested the limits on their picketing power but 
obeyed passengers waylaid by canceled flights found seats on 
competitors eastern now flies with nonstrikers and replacement 
workers 
greyhound riders on the other hand have little economic 
influence except perhaps on the balance sheet of the company the 
wayward interstate reststop concessions and the bus stop 
candynewspaper stands 
they are for the most part poor or lowincome cashpaying 
customers who cant pay the 120 for the 45minute northeast 
shuttle ride from new york to washington the 300 oneway ticket 
to chicago or the 198 roundtrip excursion fare to miami 
many are going to places the airlines dont even serve any more 
a result of the deregulation era that began more than a decade ago 
that has made greyhound the only public way to reach large swathes 
of americas heartland 
to some labormanagement experts that makes it seem even more 
incumbent on the government to guarantee the safety of greyhound 
riders some fault the transportation department for not taking a 
more aggressive stand 
i think the government position should have been stronger and 
more forthcoming in getting the parties back to the bargaining 
table said jerome rosow president of the work in america 
institute inc a consulting concern in scarsdale ny that 
specializes in labormanagement issues 
this is a public interest strike where transportation is 
affected said rosow an assistant secretary of labor from 
196971 theres a need to keep that flowing in terms of 
passenger traffic so it kind of appalled me as to why the 
government was allowing the strike to continue in the early days 
greyhound president fred currey has taken out fullpage ads in 
newspapers and ridden a few buses himself to at least symbolically 
demonstrate his concern over the passenger safety issue the 
drivers union historically accused by antiunion activists of 
promoting violence has called for prosecution of all 
strikerelated sabotage 
to some extent there is little the government can do to stop 
the violence because of the nature of the bus business itself 
putting police on every bus wouldnt deter people renegade 
strikers or uninvolved bad elements from lobbing rocks or taking 
sniper potshots from isolated overpasses on deserted highways 
even if the strike is settled the greyhound saga has aggravated 
a festering labormanagement dispute that many experts believe lies 
at the heart of the violence the right of employers to hire 
replacements for strikers 
although both sides agreed last thursday to resume talking the 
company has made its position clear on this issue 
the company cannot and will not abandon those who are helping 
it survive this senseless strike currey has said 
