writing at home and abroad has just been published as well 
as a paperback of his biography of the russian writer anton chekhov 
honors have flowed from british and us universities including 
harvard a terrific one and im very proud of that he said 
in 1975 he was knighted for services to literature 
chekhovian is a description often applied to pritchetts 
deeply human gently ironic short stories novelist elizabeth bowen 
has called him the most important english practitioner of the short 
story the times of london said of his travel writing everywhere 
he slips unobtrusively into the life of the country and lets it 
speak for itself 
the author himself says of his travel writing i have 
generally liked all the people i have met in every country i did 
not say what i thought i did not reproach or criticize them i 
listened 
in his search for a character hell listen to anybody 
salesmen housewives cab drivers barflies barbers and 
bureaucrats i knew from my own relatives that such people have 
rich imaginations pritchett says 
a passion for walking has helped he never learned to drive and 
in his younger days he walked through france spain ireland north 
america 
he still likes a stroll through regents park near the modest 
home where he lives with his wife dorothy he writes in longhand 
honing his stories through half a dozen rewrites 
in the second volume of his autobiography midnight oil 
pritchett wrote that when he went to live in france 70 years ago 
it was the beginning of a passion for identifying myself with 
people who were not my own and whose lives were governed by ideas 
alien to mine 
victor sawdon pritchett had a chaotic boyhood his father was a 
disasterprone traveling salesman and the family skipped from home 
to home in the horsedrawn cabs of edwardian london to escape 
landlords and creditors thus he called the first volume of his 
autobiography a cab at the door 
it gave me a lifelong love of travel he says with a smile 
i wanted to be a writer my grandfather put it into my head when 
i was about 12 
from his mother he got the eye for detail that carries his 
stories along so artfully she wasnt a welleducated woman but 
she was a tremendous talker and could set a scene 
he left school at 15 wrote essays and accumulated rejection 
slips at 20 he moved to paris to work in the glue trade one 
weekend he set out to walk from paris to orleans his account got 
published in london magazines 
americans are very good at reading everything and when the 
editor of the christian science monitor visited paris he insisted 
on seeing me the monitor sent him to ireland where civil war 
was raging not to write about the war itself but about the state 
of the people 
in enniskillen he met a traveling salesman an undertakers son 
who made his rounds in his fathers hearse it fascinated me and 
when i wrote it i discovered i had a gift for dialogue and a 
feeling for common speech it made me famous overnight when it was 
published by john lehmann in new writing 
the story sense of humor tells of two lovers who are 
pestered by the womans jilted boyfriend when he kills himself on 
his motorbike while pursuing them they are offered a hearse for 
the journey home and drive off with the dead mans body in the back 
pritchett remembers being absolutely bowled over by his 
meeting the irish dramatist and poet william butler yeats in 
dublin he had a marvelous lofty manner floating high above the 
level of the ordinary world and he was very kind to any young man 
he made simply marvelous speeches to me on any subject that came 
into his head he was quite an actor in himself 
between the world wars he did a lot more walking 
i didnt want to see the big cities and normal life he 
says i wanted to see abnormal life i had heard about the poor 
whites in tennessee so i went to see them in the appalachians on 
the border with north carolina 
i found one village which was absolutely incredible because 
the people spoke a very strange english and a lot of them had names 
like those in elizabethan england they were all bible christians 
very very poor and very agreeable you only had to knock on a door 
and ask to stay the night and they would take you in and feed you 
i might sleep in one room with them grandparents parents and 
children in beds all around the room 
one old man of 93 told me his name was pritchett which is not 
so common he told me i fit fought in the civil war 
country people were always surprised to find an englishman on 
their doorstep it was the same along the spanish border with 
portugal when they asked what i did for a living i couldnt say i 
was a writer because they wouldnt have understood as they never 
saw a book as i carried a camera i said i made picture postcards 
and sold them they were so poor they didnt have beds they would 
say have you brought your sack and they would fill it with 
straw 
writing has taught pritchett to suppress his own feelings and be 
open to what other people say 
i said to myself i must observe this man and understand how 
he works why he works what his attitudes and feelings are 
i made a point of believing what i heard even though it was 
fantasy because it is part of a mans nature to have fantasies it 
has been said that too many of my characters are eccentric but they 
are not really they are people who are just speaking to 
themselves 
</TEXT>
