<TEXT>
the downgrading of new york states longterm 
credit rating has shown that the problem of deteriorating credit 
quality isnt confined to the muchmaligned junk bond market 
citing concerns about stalled negotiations to close a widening 
budget deficit standard amp poors corp last week dropped its 
rating on the states longterm general obligation bonds by two 
notches to singlea it also gave a lower rating to a new state 
shortterm financing 
the move left new york with the thirdlowest rating among the 
states ahead only of lowly louisiana and massachusetts 
the longterm downgrade applied only to 39 billion in bonds 
outstanding but the move carried big implications for the 700 
billion municipal bond market 
about 10 percent of the outstanding bonds in the market come 
from new york or various municipalities school districts and other 
entities in the state including new york city most of those 
entities depend on the state for a large portion of their revenues 
so cuts in the state budget could hit them hard 
even if theres some modest adjustment every school district 
in the state theoretically could be affected said bob 
chamberlain head of municipal research at dean witter reynolds inc 
the downgrade didnt have a big initial impact because the 
states problems including a recession in its key financial 
services industry and sluggishness in tax receipts have been 
increasingly evident in recent months 
theres been a downtrend over the past six to eight to 10 
months says neal atterman director of municipal research at 
kidder peabody amp co 
still the rating change forced the state to pay about 10 basis 
points more in yield to sell 775 million in tax and revenue 
anticipation notes to help close its budget gap estimates mike 
delaney a partner in the municipal bond department at goldman 
sachs amp co the firm underwrote nearly half last weeks issue 
the budget pressures facing new york are intensifying across the 
northeast where sluggish economic growth and a weak real estate 
market are crimping state revenue growth 
lawmakers in massachusetts have been struggling to get the 
states finances in order for more than a year standard amp poors 
recently lowered its ratings on connecticuts longterm debt by one 
notch to doublea because of recurring budgetary problems 
hyman grossman managing director in charge of municipals at 
sampp says weakness in the economy has led to shortfalls in personal 
income tax and corporate tax receipts in new york 
his suggestion a 10 percent income tax surcharge that would 
raise about 15 billion perhaps enough to close the budget gap 
for the year that began sunday thats tough medicine in these 
political times 
but grossman says when it comes to basic fiscal integrity 
politics has to be shunted aside 
george leung managing director of state ratings at moodys 
investors service inc says that while the states economy causes 
some underlying concerns the main problem now is getting new 
yorks legislative leaders and gov mario cuomo to agree on real 
measures to cut the deficit 
theres certainly an ability here they just have to deal with 
the problem he said 
although most attention has focused on the northeasts problems 
less severe cash shortages are evident elsewhere including 
southeast states like florida georgia and tennessee says atterman 
of kidder peabody 
many states are suffering from changes in federal government 
policy in recent years that have imposed increased spending 
requirements on the states while reducing federal aid at the same 
time 
the number of states and the variety of states that are 
either expecting a deficit or are having cash difficulties is 
rather startling he sas 
i think very gradually theres been some concern about a 
worsening of credit quality in the municipal market generally says 
delaney of goldman sachs you saw it in the junk market you saw 
it in the corporate market and youre seeing it in the municipal 
market 
the deterioration hasnt pushed up bond yields that much to date 
because of a dearth in the volume of new issues atterman says the 
pace of new issues is off about 20 percent so far this year in 
large part because a rise in interest rates generally has 
discouraged some potential borrowers 
nevertheless if and when we do see more volume in the market 
were going to see increased differentiation in yields between 
different credit risks he says 
